But such things were inconceivable in New York , and unsettling to think of . 
He was reminded of this by trying to picture the society in which the Countess Olenska had lived and suffered , and also perhaps tasted mysterious joys . 
He remembered with what amusement she had told him that her grandmother Mingott and the Wellands objected to her living in a Bohemian quarter given over to people who wrote . 
It was not the peril but the poverty that her family disliked but that shade escaped her , and she supposed they considered literature compromising . 
